		<table width="90%" bgcolor="" style="border-collapse: collapse; border-left-width:1; border-right-width: 1; border-top-style: solid; border-left-style: solid; border-right-style: solid; border-bottom-style: solid; border-top-width: 1; border-bottom-width: 1" bordercolor="#FFFFFF" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" ID="Table2">  
		<tr>
			<td align="left" valign="top" background="/images/necrotableheader2.gif">
				<font width="100%" face="verdana" size="1" color=white><b>Maiden's Eye - Charm killing</b>
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr bgcolor="#ffebdc">
			<td align="left" valign="top" valign="top">
				<font face="verdana" size="1" color=white>
				written by <b>iranicus</b> on <b>3/12/2003 8:36:10 AM</b>
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr bgcolor="#37437B">
			<td align="left" valign="top" valign="top">
				<font face="verdana" size="1" color=white><blockquote><br>
				Zone: Maiden's Eye<br>Levels: 54-60<br>Risks: High<br>Loot: Crap<br>XP: Good<br>Method: Charm<br><br>This is a guide that will present some charm killing strategies. It's not the only one, of course, but it is what I did and it worked quite well.<br><br>Easiest way to get to Maidede's Eye is to get a port to Downshroud Peaks then run to Maidens. From Nexus, you would go Netherbian Lair -> Downshroud Peaks -> Maiden's Eye. As you zone in,  head right along the wall and set camp right after the first hill, before the Coterie camp. Spell lineup sugestion:<br><br>- Deflux / ToN<br>- FD<br>- ST<br>- Thrall of Bones<br>- Immobilize<br>- BoD / Vex<br>- Lich/Demi/Arch Lich - swap with Shackle of Spirit<br>- Dooming (if you have epic, you can load fast dot here)<br><br>I used as pets Skeletal Drudges. Reanimated Drudges are higher level but most are too high for Thrall, you might have to spend some time to find a lower level one. If this is your first attempt at charm killing, I would suggest you stick with Skeletal Drudges. I used as buff Augment Death from the Velious pants. You can use, of course, your level 55 buff Augmentation of Death, but it's a bit safer without it and mobs die fast enough already. Have SoW on you at all times (get some SoW potions)<br><br>Now go out in the open, find a Skeletal Drudge, Thrall it and get it back to camp. Buff it and tell it to /guard here. If charm breaks, just run , ST and recharm. If a pet resists charm too often, or breaks it too often then kill it and get another one.<br><br>As long as you have a charmed pet, you will want to chain pull. Run ahead, target a bat, pull with Slow, run to pet. When you pass pet, tell it to attack then root the bat. Snare it asap. Then target your pet and go to a safe distance. Keep the mob rooted/snare at ALL times. If charm breaks, then just ST quick, recharm, re-send pet. Once you get the hang of it, you can get mobs even before your pet kills the current one and root-park them. A hasted skel can mow through bats and undead robed guys, not much HP loss. Once in a while you get a ravenous wolf add. Those have a buttload of HPs and hit hard, you cant slow them. Pet cant usually kill them. I was usually letting pet die, then just root dot the wolf. You need another pet after this. You can pull toilers too, they cant be slowed but they die fast from a hasted skel. Reanimated Drudges also are ok, you can slow them. I didnt bother with the Coterie, but you can pull them too. <br><br>Some tips:<br>- Have SoW at all times<br>- Keep your mob rooted / snared at all times<br>- Keep your charmed pet targeted all the time when you are not casting on the mob you kill<br>- Dump pet if he resists charm or breaks it too often<br><br>If you're focused, then you should do fine. The only time when it can get hairy is when charm breaks as you bring a mob to your pet. If this happens, you can either zone them or, what I did, just run around, root the mob and ST/recharm pet. Just avoid being hit, especially by your pet since it's hasted. <br><br>&nbsp;<br>
			</td>
		</tr>
